VLib

All-round header-only c++ library.

Language Dialect

VLib is developed for the language dialect c++20.

Operating Systems

VLib supports operating systems macos & linux.

Limits

vlib::limits
Numeric limits structure.
template <typename Type> 
struct limits;

Template parameters

typename
Type
Required

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
int int_max = vlib::limits<int>::max;

Range

vlib::Range
Iterate a certain range.
template <typename Iter = Forwards, typename Type = ullong> 
struct Range;

Template parameters

typename
Iter
typename
Type

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>

// Iterate from 0 till 1000000.
for (auto& i: vlib::Range(1000000)) { ... }

// Iterate from 0 till 100.
for (auto& i: vlib::Range(0, 100)) { ... }

// Safe while loop.
auto x = vlib::Range(0, 10);
while (++x) { ... }

// Iterate from 1000000 till 0.
for (auto& i: vlib::Range<vlib::Backwards>(1000000)) { ... }

// Iterate from 100 till 0.
for (auto& i: vlib::Range<vlib::Backwards>(100, 0)) { ... }

// Warning!
// This causes an infinite loop.
while (++vlib::Range(0, 10)) { ... }

Random

vlib::random
Static random structure.
struct random;

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
vlib::random:: ... ();

Generate

vlib::random::generate
Get a random integer integral type between min and max.
Static
Member 
template <typename Type> 
requires (!is_short<Type>::value &&is_any_integer<Type>::value)
inline static 
Type generate(const Type& min = 0, const Type& max = limits<Type>::max);

Template parameters

typename
Type
Required

Parameters

const Type&
min
const Type&
max

Return

Type
The return type is Type.

Examples

auto x = vlib::random::generate<uint>();
auto x = vlib::random::generate<uint>(0, 10);
auto x = vlib::random::generate<ullong>();
auto x = vlib::random::generate<ullong>(0.0, 9999999999999999999.0);

Generate

Static
Member

Template parameters

typename
Type
Required

Parameters

const Type&
base

Return

Type

Examples

vlib::random::generate<float>() ==> 0.283957;
vlib::random::generate<float>(0.1) ==> 0.082981;
vlib::random::generate<float>(0.001) ==> 0.000284;

Colors

vlib::colors
Static colors structure.

The available colors are:
• vlib::colors::black
• vlib::colors::red
• vlib::colors::green
• vlib::colors::yellow
• vlib::colors::blue
• vlib::colors::magenta
• vlib::colors::cyan
• vlib::colors::gray
• vlib::colors::bold
• vlib::colors::italic
• vlib::colors::end.
struct colors;

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
vlib::print(tostr(vlib::colors::bold, "Hello World!", vlib::colors::end));

Args

Parameters

args

To char

vlib::tochar
Cast to a char.
- Currently only supports casts from a digit [0..9].
template <typename... Args> inline constexpr 
char tochar(Args&&... args);

Template parameters

typename...
Args

Parameters

Args&&...
args

Return

char
The return type is char.

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
vlib::tochar(0) ==> '0';
vlib::tochar(9) ==> '9';
vlib::tochar(100) ==> '0'; // ERROR: the digit's range is [0..9].

To numeric

vlib::tonumeric
Cast to any numeric.
template <typename Cast, typename... Args> inline constexpr 
Cast tonumeric(Args&&... args);

Template parameters

typename
Cast
Required
typename...
Args

Parameters

Args&&...
args

Return

Cast
The return type is Cast.

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
vlib::tonumeric<int>("1") ==> 1;

To string

tostr
Concatenate arg(s) to a String.
template <typename... Args> inline constexpr 
String tostr(Args&&... args);

Template parameters

typename...
Args

Parameters

Args&&...
args

Return

String
The return type is String.

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
tostr("Hello", " ", "World!") ==> "Hello World!";
tostr(true) ==> "true";
tostr("Bool: ", true) ==> "Bool: true";
tostr(1) ==> "1";
tostr("Int: ", 1) ==> "Int: 1";
tostr(0.1) ==> "0.100000";
tostr("Double: ", 0.1) ==> "Double: 0.100000";
tostr(1, " == ", 1, " = ", 1 == 1) ==> "1 == 1 = true";

Location

vlib::Loc
Source location type.
struct Loc;

Examples

// Get the source location.
#include <vlib/types.h>
vlib::Loc x = vlib::Loc::get();
vlib::print(x.path(), ':', x.line(), ':', x.column(), ": ", x.path());

Exception

vlib::Exception
Exception type.

Define preprocessor variable #define vlib_enable_trace true to enable a stacktrace.
Define preprocessor variable #define vlib_max_trace 32 to set a max stacktrace depth, the default value is 32.
The stacktrace only works properly when the program is compiled without optimization, and compiled with flags -g and -rdynamic for linux.
struct Exception;

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
vlib::Exception x (...);

Pipe

vlib::Pipe
Pipe type.
struct Pipe;

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>

// Dump to the stdout console.
vlib::out << "Hello World! \n";

// Dump to the stderr console.
vlib::err << "Error: ... \n";

// Create a class that can be dumped using "Pipe".
class myclass {
    constexpr
    const char* c_str() const {
    return "Hello World!";
}
friend
auto& operator <<(vlib::Pipe& pipe, const myclass& obj) {
return pipe << obj.c_str();
}
};

Reverse

vlib::Bool::reverse
Reverses a Bool with value true to false and a Bool with value false to true.
Member 
constexpr 
vlib::Bool reverse(); 

constexpr 
vlib::Bool& reverse_r();

Return

vlib::Bool
Function reverse returns a new Bool object while function reverse_r updates the current object and returns a reference to the current object.

Examples

vlib::Bool x = false;
vlib::Bool y = x.reverse(); y ==> true;

vlib::Numeric
Numeric type.

The following aliases are defined:
typedef Numeric<int> Int
typedef Numeric<uint> UInt
typedef Numeric<float> Float
typedef Numeric<double> Double
typedef Numeric<ldouble> LDouble
typedef Numeric<long> Long
typedef Numeric<llong> LLong
typedef Numeric<ullong> Len.
template <typename Type> 
requires (is_any_numeric<Type>::value)

struct Numeric;

Power of

vlib::Numeric::pow
Calculate the power of with a numeric.

Function pow_r updates the current object, while pow creates a copy.

Parameter x can be negative when the numeric is floating. The power of will than act as a division. For example Double(10.0).pow(-1) will return 0.1. The underlying formula is numeric / pow(abs(numeric), (-x)+1).
Member 
template <typename Num> 
requires (
    !is_floating<Type>::value &&
    (
        is_any_numeric<Num>::value ||
        is_any_numeric<typename Num::value_type>::value
    )
)
constexpr 
vlib::Numeric pow(const Num& x);

Reverse

vlib::Array::reverse_r
Reverse the array.

Function reverse_r updates the current array, while reverse creates a copy.
Member 
constexpr 
vlib::Array& reverse_r(); 

constexpr 
vlib::Array reverse();

Return

vlib::Array&
The return type is vlib::Array&.

Examples

// Reverse an array.
Array<int> x = {1, 2, 3, 4};
x.reverse_r(); x ==> {4, 3, 2, 1};

// Do not use reverse_r for iterations.
// Since this is quite inefficient.
// Use "iterate()" instead.
for (auto& i: x.reverse_r()) {}     <-- Incorrect
for (auto& i: x.iterate<Backwards>()) {}  <-- Correct.

Reverse

vlib::String::reverse_r

Function reverse_r updates the current array, while reverse creates a copy.
Member 
constexpr 
vlib::String& reverse_r(); 

constexpr 
vlib::String reverse();

Return

vlib::String&
The return type is vlib::String&.

Examples

// Reverse an array.
Array<int> x = {1, 2, 3, 4};
x.reverse_r(); x ==> {4, 3, 2, 1};

// Do not use reverse_r for iterations.
// Since this is quite inefficient.
// Use "iterate()" instead.
for (auto& i: x.reverse_r()) {}     <-- Incorrect
for (auto& i: x.iterate<Backwards>()) {}  <-- Correct.

Code patterns

vlib::Code::code_patterns
Used to include / exclude characters from Code operations.

struct code_patterns {
    bool    exclude_strings = false;    // exclude strings.
    bool    exclude_chars = false;      // exclude chars.
    bool    exclude_comments = false;   // exclude comments.
    bool    exclude_escaped = false;    // exclude items preceded by an escape character.
    int     parentheses_depth = -1;     // required parentheses depth (-1 to ignore).
    int     brackets_depth = -1;        // required brackets depth (-1 to ignore).
    int     curly_brackets_depth = -1;  // required curly brackets depth (-1 to ignore).
    int     template_depth = -1;        // required template depth (-1 to ignore).
};
.
Member 
struct code_patterns;

Find code

vlib::Code::find_code
Find a substring in the code.

Offers special exclude / include patterns.
Member 
constexpr 
ullong find_code(
    const char* to_find, 
    const Len& sindex = 0, 
    const Len& eindex = NPos::npos, 
    const code_patterns& patterns = {false, false, false, false, -1, -1, -1, -1}
);

Parameters

const char*
to_find
Required
const Len&
sindex
const Len&
eindex
const code_patterns&
patterns

Return

ullong
Returns the start index of the substring when the substring is found.
Returns vlib::NPos::npos when the substring is not found.

Examples

vlib::Code code ("Hi \"X\" Ho");
code.find("X"); ==> 4
code.find_code("X", 0, NPos::npos, { .exclude_strings = true } ); ==> npos

Reverse

vlib::String::reverse_r

Function reverse_r updates the current array, while reverse creates a copy.
Member 
constexpr 
vlib::String& reverse_r(); 

constexpr 
vlib::String reverse();

Return

vlib::String&
The return type is vlib::String&.

Examples

// Reverse an array.
Array<int> x = {1, 2, 3, 4};
x.reverse_r(); x ==> {4, 3, 2, 1};

// Do not use reverse_r for iterations.
// Since this is quite inefficient.
// Use "iterate()" instead.
for (auto& i: x.reverse_r()) {}     <-- Incorrect
for (auto& i: x.iterate<Backwards>()) {}  <-- Correct.

Iterate

vlib::Dict::iterate
Iterate from index till index.

Optionally iterate the dictionary reversed.
Member 
template <typename Iter = Forwards, typename... Args> 
requires (is_Forwards<Iter>::value ||is_Backwards<Iter>::value)
constexpr 
Dict::Iter<Iter> iterate(Args&&... args);

Template parameters

typename
Iter
typename...
Args

Parameters

Args&&...
args
The arguments for indexes().

Return

Dict::Iter<Iter>
The return type is Dict::Iter<Iter>.

Examples

dic_t<...> x = ...;
for (auto& [key, value]: x.iterate()) {
print(*key, ": ", *value);
}
for (auto& [key, value]: x.iterate(1, 9)) { // iterate indexes 1 till 8.
print(*key, ": ", *value);
}
for (auto& [key, value]: x.iterate<Backwards>()) {
print(*key, ": ", *value);
}

Indexes

vlib::Dict::indexes
Iterate the indexes from index till index.

Optionally iterate the indexes reversed.

The start and end indexes of a reversed iteration are just like a normal iteration, so index 0 is the first index.

auto indexes();

constexpr 
auto indexes(const Len& sindex, const Len& eindex = NPos::npos);

typename
Iter

Examples

The arguments for indexes().

Return

Dict::Iter<Iter>
The return type is Dict::Iter<Iter>.

Examples

dic_t<...> x = ...;
for (auto& [key, value]: x.iterate()) {
print(*key, ": ", *value);
}
for (auto& [key, value]: x.iterate(1, 9)) { // iterate indexes 1 till 8.
print(*key, ": ", *value);
}
for (auto& [key, value]: x.iterate<Backwards>()) {
print(*key, ": ", *value);
}

Indexes

vlib::Dict::indexes
Iterate the indexes from index till index.

Optionally iterate the indexes reversed.

The start and end indexes of a reversed iteration are just like a normal iteration, so index 0 is the first index.
Member 
template <typename Iter = Forwards> 
requires (is_Forwards<Iter>::value ||is_Backwards<Iter>::value)
constexpr 
auto indexes(); 

template <typename Iter = Forwards> 
requires (is_Forwards<Iter>::value ||is_Backwards<Iter>::value)
constexpr 
auto indexes(const Len& sindex, const Len& eindex = NPos::npos);

Template parameters

typename
Iter

Examples

for (auto& i: x.iterate(1, 2)) { ... }

Dataframe

vlib::DataFrame
Type for 1D and 2D dataframes.
struct DataFrame;

Notes

A dataframe can be the following types:
- vlib::df::types::null
- vlib::df::types::integer
- vlib::df::types::floating
- vlib::df::types::str
- vlib::df::types::df.

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
vlib::DataFrame df({
    {0, 2345.4, "A"},
    {1, 4363.3, "B"},
    {2, 7895.1, "C"},
});

Constructor

x

Examples

vlib::DataFrame df({
    {0, 2345.4, "A"},
    {1, 4363.3, "B"},
    {2, 7895.1, "C"},
});

Parameters

const Len&
window
Required

Return

Notes

Values that can't apply a full window will have type vlib::df::types::null.

Dump

vlib::SpeedTest::dump
Dump the performance test.
/
void dump() {
m_labels.append("Total");
ullong total = 0;
for (auto& i: m_speeds) {
total += i;
}
m_speeds.append(total);
ullong max_len = 0;
for (auto& i: m_labels) {
if (i.len() > max_len) {
max_len = i.len();
}
}
for (auto& index: m_labels.indexes()) {
vlib::out << m_labels[index] << ':';
for (int i = 0; i < (int) (max_len - m_labels[index].len()); ++i) {
vlib::out << ' ';
}
vlib::out << ' ' << float(m_speeds[index]) / 1000 << 's' << '.' << '\n';
}
}.
Member 
void dump();

Return

void
The return type is void.

Thread

vlib::Thread
Thread type.

Can be used to use as a base class for another type.

Can be used to start a thread function.
template <typename Derived = vlib::Null> 
struct Thread;

Template parameters

typename
Derived

Notes

- The thread acts as a shared pointer.

Examples

// --------------------------------------------------------
// Thread class.

#include <vlib/types.h>

// Create a thread class.
struct some_thread : public vlib::Thread<some_thread> {
    
    // The thread run function.
    void*  run(void) {
    vlib::print("Starting thread: ", id()));
return NULL;
}

};

int main() {
some_thread thread;
thread.start();
thread.join();
return 0;
}

// --------------------------------------------------------
// Thread function.

#include <vlib/types.h>

// A thread function without args.
void* some_func(void*) {
vlib::print("Hello World!");
return NULL;
}

// The thread function.
void* some_func_with_args(vlib::String day, vlib::String name) {
vlib::print("Good ", day, " ", name, "!");
return NULL;
}

int main() {

// Start a thread without arguments.
vlib::FThread thread0;
thread0.start(some_func);
thread0.join();

// Start a thread with arguments.
vlib::FThread thread1;
thread1.start(some_func_with_args, "Sunday", "World");
thread1.join();

return 0;

}

Thread Pool

vlib::ThreadPool
Thread Pool type.

Currently only supports function threads.
struct ThreadPool;

Examples

// ---------------------------------------------------------
// Standard thread pool.

// Include.
#include <vlib/types.h>

// A thread function.
void* some_func(const Int& i) {
vlib::print("Running thread: ", i, ".");
return NULL;
}

int main() {

// Start a thread without arguments.
vlib::ThreadPool thread_pool(25); // maximum 25 threads.

// Iterate threads.
Int index = 0;
for (auto& thread: thread_pool) {
thread.start(some_func, index);
++index;
}
for (auto& thread: thread_pool) {
thread.join();
}
return 0;

}

// ---------------------------------------------------------
// Managed thread pool.
// The current example creates 100 threads.
// But only 25 will be running simultaneously.

// Include.
#include <vlib/types.h>

// A thread function.
void* some_func(const Int& i) {
vlib::print("Running thread: ", i, ".");
return NULL;
}

int main() {

// Start a thread without arguments.
vlib::ThreadPool thread_pool(25); // maximum 25 threads.

// Iterate threads.
for (auto& index: range(100)) {
thread_pool.start(somefunc, index);
}
return 0;

}

Create a user.

Member 
static inline constexpr 
void create(
    const char* name, 
    const char* realname, 
    const String& pass, 
    int uid = -1, 
    int gid = -1, 
    bool superuser = false, 
    const char* homes = "/home/", 
    const char* shell = "/bin/bash"
);

Parameters

const char*
name
Required
The username.
const char*
realname
Required
The user's real name.
const String&
pass
Required
int
uid
The user's id, leave -1 to assign automatically.
int
gid
bool
superuser
Whether to grant the new user root priviliges.
const char*
homes
The homes path, base path of the user's home path, not the user's home path itself.
The function's default value for linux systems is /home/ while the default value for MacOS is /Users/.
const char*
shell

Return

void
The return type is void.

Notes

- Must be executed with root priviliges.
- In order to create the user the password will be exposed to execl().
- MacOS: When a new superuser has been created it requires a reboot before the superuser changes take effect.

x.type() == Path::types::file; ==> true;

Create directory

vlib::Path::mkdir
Create a directory.

No exceptions will be thrown when the path already exists.

Function mkdir() creates a directory for the main path. While function mkdir_p() recursively creates the base directories of the path when they do not exist. Therefore mkdir_p() is similair to $ mkdir -p /tmp/dir1/dir2/dir3.
Member 
void mkdir(ushort permission = 0740); 

void mkdir_p(ushort permission = 0740);

Parameters

ushort
permission

Return

void
The return type is void.

Examples

vlib::Path x("/tmp/dir");
x.mkdir();

Length

Length

bool

Return

The return type is vlib::String&.

Examples

String x = "Something before {Hello World!} {Hi {Hello Universe!} There} {Hello Earth!} something after.";
x.slice_r('{', '}', 0) => "Hello World!"
x.slice_r('{', '}', 1) => "Hi {Hello Universe!} There"
x.slice_r('{', '}', 2) => "Hello Earth!"
x.slice_r('{', '}', 2, true) => "{Hello Earth!}"

Reverse

vlib::String::reverse_r
Reverse the array.

Function reverse_r updates the current array, while reverse creates a copy.
Member 
constexpr 
vlib::String& reverse_r(); 

constexpr 
vlib::String reverse();

Return

vlib::String&
The return type is vlib::String&.

Examples

// Reverse an array.
Array<int> x = {1, 2, 3, 4};
x.reverse_r(); x ==> {4, 3, 2, 1};

// Do not use reverse_r for iterations.
// Since this is quite inefficient.
// Use "iterate()" instead.
for (auto& i: x.reverse_r()) {}     <-- Incorrect
for (auto& i: x.iterate<Backwards>()) {}  <-- Correct.

File

vlib::File
File type.

Object File acts as a shared pointer, use File::copy() to create a real copy without any links.

The available file modes are (can not be combined):
- vlib::file::r.
- vlib::file::w.
- vlib::file::a.
struct File;

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
vlib::File file("/tmp/myfile.txt");

Script

vlib::Script
Script type.
- Automatically adds a newline after each constructor Arg.
- Beware of the fact that a Script executed by Proc will be saved to /tmp/script_$uid_XXXXXXXX with permission 0770, the path will be deleted upon any exit.
struct Script;

x.replace_end_r(" >?"); x ==> "Hello World!";

Function slice_r updates the current array, while slice creates a copy.
Member

vlib::String& slice_r(
    Type dstart, 
    Type dend, 
    uint depth, 
    Length sindex = 0, 
    Length eindex = internal::npos, 
    bool include = false
);

    Type dstart, 
    Type dend,

    bool include = false
);

Parameters

Type
dstart
Required
The start delimiter, example {.
Type
dend
Required
The end delimiter, example }.
uint

Required
The depth of the occurences.
Length
sindex
Length
eindex
bool
include

Return

vlib::String&
The return type is vlib::String&.

Examples

String x = "Something before {Hello World!} {Hi {Hello Universe!} There} {Hello Earth!} something after.";
x.slice_r('{', '}', 0) => "Hello World!"
x.slice_r('{', '}', 1) => "Hi {Hello Universe!} There"
x.slice_r('{', '}', 2) => "Hello Earth!"
x.slice_r('{', '}', 2, true) => "{Hello Earth!}"

Reverse

vlib::String::reverse_r
Reverse the array.

Function reverse_r updates the current array, while reverse creates a copy.
Member 
constexpr 
vlib::String& reverse_r(); 

constexpr 
vlib::String reverse();

Return

vlib::String&
The return type is vlib::String&.

Examples

// Reverse an array.
Array<int> x = {1, 2, 3, 4};
x.reverse_r(); x ==> {4, 3, 2, 1};

// Do not use reverse_r for iterations.
// Since this is quite inefficient.
// Use "iterate()" instead.
for (auto& i: x.reverse_r()) {}     <-- Incorrect
for (auto& i: x.iterate<Backwards>()) {}  <-- Correct.

Process

vlib::Proc
Process type.
- By default it executes a bash script / command.
struct Proc;

Examples

#include <vlib/types.h>
vlib::Proc proc0;
if (proc0.execute("echo Hello World!") != 0) { ... }

// Execute a synchronous process.
vlib::Proc proc1 { .async = true };
if (proc1.execute("echo Hello World!") == 0) {
...
if (proc1.join() == 0) {
...
}
}

// The avaiable construct options and their default values.
vlib::Proc proc2 {
.input = "",
.input_len = 0,
.timeout = 15000,
.async = false,
}

Join

vlib::Proc::join
Await the process.
- Will be called automatically inside execute() when async is false.
- Always calls close(), including when an error or timeout has occured.
- Automatically calls parse_exit_status() on a successfull join().
Member 
int join();

Return

int
The return type is int.

Execute

vlib::Proc::execute
Execute the process.
- Returns 0 upon success.
- The arguments must be of type const char*.
- Beware of the fact that a Script executed by execute() will be saved to the assigned Script path, with the assigned Script permission. The path will be deleted upon any exit.
Member 
int execute(const char* arg);

Parameters

const char*
arg
Required

Return

int
The return type is int.

Examples

// Execute a bash process.
Proc proc;
int status = proc.execute("echo Hello World!");

// Is equal to.
status = proc.execute("/bin/bash", "-c", "bash", "echo Hello World!");

// Execute a zsh process.
status = proc.execute("/bin/zsh", "-exec", "-c", "echo Hello World!");

Start

vlib::Daemon::start
Start the daemon.

- Requires root priviliges.
/
void start() {
if (getuid() != 0) {
throw DaemonError("Root privileges required.");
}
if (!m_path.exists()) {
throw DaemonError(tostr("Daemon \"", m_path, "\" does not exist."));
}
#if OSID == 0
String command ("systemctl start ", 16);
#elif OSID == 1
String command ("launchctl start ", 16);
#endif
command << m_settings.name;
Proc proc;
if (proc.execute(command) != 0 || proc.exit_status() != 0) {
throw DaemonError("Failed to start the daemon.");
}
}.

The return type is void.

restart

vlib::Daemon::restart
Restart the daemon.

- Requires root priviliges.
/
void restart() {
if (getuid() != 0) {
throw DaemonError("Root privileges required.");
}
if (!m_path.exists()) {
throw DaemonError(tostr("Daemon \"", m_path, "\" does not exist."));
}
#if OSID == 0
String command ("systemctl restart ", 18);
command << m_settings.name;
#elif OSID == 1
String command ("launchctl stop ", 15);
command << m_settings.name;
command.concat_r(" && launchctl start ", 20);
command << m_settings.name;
#endif
Proc proc;
if (proc.execute(command) != 0 || proc.exit_status() != 0) {
throw DaemonError("Failed to restart the daemon.");
}
}.
Member 
void restart();

Return

void
The return type is void.

tail

vlib::Daemon::tail
Tail the daemon logs.

- Requires root priviliges.
/
String tail(const Int& lines = 100) {
if (getuid() != 0) {
throw DaemonError("Root privileges required.");
}
if (!m_path.exists()) {
throw DaemonError(tostr("Daemon \"", m_path, "\" does not exist."));
}
String command;
#if OSID == 0
command = tostr("sudo journalctl -u ", m_settings.name, ".service --no-pager -n ", lines);
#elif OSID == 1
throw OSError(tostr("Operating system \"MacOS\" is not yet supported."));
lines + 1; // to ignore unused parameter.
#endif
Proc proc;
if (proc.execute(command) != 0 || proc.exit_status() != 0) {
throw DaemonError("Failed to tail the daemon.");
}
return proc.err_or_out();
}.
Member 
String tail(const Int& lines = 100);

Parameters

const Int&
lines

Return

String
The return type is String.

Compile

vlib::compile
Compile c++ code.

The supported fields for the configuration json are: [compiler, input, output, std, include_paths, library_paths, linked_libraries, other_flags].

Path values in the configuration file may use $SOURCE which will be replaced with the source_dir parameter.

Every value in the configuration json can either be the value to use, or a nested json with os specific values.
For example "other_flags": ["-g"] may also be "other_flags": {"macos": ["-g"], "linux": ["-g", "-rdynamic"]}.
The supported os types are macos and linux.

An example configuration json.
    {
    "compiler": "clang++",
    "input": "$SOURCE/build.cpp",
    "output": "$SOURCE/bin/build",
    "std": "c++2b",
    "include_paths": [
    "/opt/vinc/include/",
    "/opt/homebrew/opt/openssl@3.1/include/"
    ],
    "library_paths": [
    "/opt/homebrew/opt/openssl@3.1/lib/"
    ],
    "linked_libraries": {
        "macos": [
        "-lssl",
        "-lcrypto",
        "-lz"
        ],
        "linux": [
        "-lssl",
        "-lcrypto",
        "-lz",
        "-lcrypt",
        "-ldl"
        ]
    },
    "other_flags": [
    "-g",
    "-rdynamic",
    "-fsanitize=undefined",
    "-Wno-unknown-escape-sequence"
    ]
}
.
This function is mainly implemented for other vinc libraries so it may be subject to change.
void compile(
    const Json& config, 
    const Path& source_dir = {}, 
    const Path& config_path = {}, 
    const Bool& log = false
);

Parameters

const Json&
config
Required
The compile configuration.
const Path&
source_dir
The path of the source directory. Used to replace $SOURCE in the configuration json.
const Path&
config_path
The path to the configuration json.
const Bool&
log
Allow logging to the console.

Return

void
The return type is void.

Zip

vlib::Zip
Create or extract a zip archive.

Supports zip archives that exceed 4GB (zip64).

Only supports zip files that are on a single disk.

Only supports the following extra fields.
- ZIP64 extended information extra field.
- Info-ZIP Unix Extra Field (type 2).
All unsupported extra fields are silently ignored.
This class is experimental and still in development.
struct Zip;

Examples

#include <vlib/compression.h>
vlib::Zip zip;
...

Entry

vlib::Zip::Entry
A zip archive file entry.

An entry contains the following attributes:
uint64_t        offset = 0;             // file header offset.
uint16_t        mode = 0;               // file mode directly from assigned "st_mode".
uint16_t        uid = 0;                // uid of the path.
uint16_t        gid = 0;                // gid of the path.
uint16_t        mod_time = 0;           // mod time of the path
uint16_t        mod_date = 0;           // mod date of the path.
uint16_t  compression_method = 8; // the compression method.
uint64_t        compressed_len = 0;     // length of uncompressed data.
uint64_t        uncompressed_len = 0;   // length of compressed data.
uint32_t        crc = 0;                // crc32 checksum.
String          name;                   // sub path.
String          data;                   // compressed data.
.
Member 
struct Entry;

Examples

vlib::Zip zip;
zip.read("/tmp/archive.zip");
for (auto& entry: zip.entries()) {
...
}

Compression Level

vlib::Zip::compression_level

Member
Attribute

auto& compression_level();

Examples

zip.compression_level() = ...;

Entries

vlib::Zip::entries
Get all the file names from the archive.

The archive must have been initialized by one of the Zip member functions. For example read().
Member
Attribute 
constexpr 
Array<Zip::Entry>&entries();

Return

Array<Zip::Entry>&
The return type is Array<Zip::Entry>&.

Examples

// Read a zip archive.
vlib::Zip zip;
zip.read("/tmp/archive.zip");

// Get the entries.
for (auto& entry: zip.entries()) {
print(entry.name);
}

File names

vlib::Zip::file_names
Get all the file names from the archive.

The archive must have been initialized by one of the Zip member functions. For example read().
It is much faster to iterate the entries with entries(). Since file_names() creates a copy of each file name.
Member 
constexpr 
Array<String> file_names();

Return

Array<String>
The return type is Array<String>.

Examples

// Read a zip archive.
vlib::Zip zip;
zip.read("/tmp/archive.zip");

// Iterate the files names.
// Not recommended since it copies each file name.
for (auto& name: zip.file_names()) {
print(name);
}

// Recommended version:
for (auto& entry: zip.entries()) {
print(entry.name);
}

Content types

vlib::http::content_type::content_types
HTTP content types, does not include all available content types.
enum content_types {
    undefined = 0, // must always remain zero for vweb.
    unknown = 1,
    json = 2,
    xml = 3,
    html = 4,
    plain = 5,
    css = 6,
    js = 7,
};

Examples

#include <vlib/sockets/http.h>
vlib::http::content_type_t content_type = vlib::http::content_type::json;

vlib::http::method::methods
HTTP methods.
enum methods {
    undefined = 0,
    get = 1,
    head = 2,
    post = 3,
    put = 4,
    del = 5,
    connect = 6,
    options = 7,
    trace = 8,
    patch = 9,
};

#include <vlib/sockets/http.h>

Status

vlib::http::status::statuses
HTTP status codes.
enum statuses {
    undefined = 0,
    continue_ = 100,
    switching_protocols = 101,
    early_hints = 103,
    success = 200,
    created = 201,
    accepted = 202,
    no_auth_info = 203,
    no_content = 204,
    reset_content = 205,
    partial_content = 206,
    multiple_choices = 300,
    moved_permanently = 301,
    found = 302,
    see_other = 303,
    not_modified = 304,
    temporary_redirect = 307,
    permanent_redirect = 308,
    bad_request = 400,
    unauthorized = 401,
    payment_required = 402,
    forbidden = 403,
    not_found = 404,
    method_not_allowed = 405,
    not_acceptable = 406,
    proxy_auth_required = 407,
    Requestimeout = 408,
    conflict = 409,
    gone = 410,
    length_required = 411,
    precondition_failed = 412,
    payload_too_large = 413,
    uri_too_large = 414,
    unsupported_media_type = 415,
    range_not_statisfiable = 416,
    expectation_failed = 417,
    imateapot = 418,
    unprocessable_entity = 422,
    too_early = 425,
    upgrade_required = 426,
    precondition_required = 428,
    too_many_requests = 429,
    request_header_fields_too_large = 431,
    unavailable_for_legal_reasons = 451,
    internal_server_error = 500,
    not_implemented = 501,
    bad_gateway = 502,
    service_unvailable = 503,
    gateway_timeout = 504,
    http_version_not_supported = 505,
    variant_also_negotiates = 506,
    insufficient_storage = 507,
    loop_detected = 508,
    not_extended = 510,
    network_auth_required = 511,
    // Custom statuses.
    two_factor_auth_required = 601,
};

Examples

#include <vlib/sockets/http.h>
short success = vlib::http::status::success;

Version

vlib::http::version::versions
HTTP versions.

Only supports HTTP versions [0.9, 1.0, 1.1, 2.0].
enum versions {
    undefined = 0,
    v0_9 = 9,
    v1_0 = 10,
    v1_1 = 11,
    v2_0 = 20,
};

Response

vlib::http::Response
HTTP response type.
struct Response;

Notes

- Only supports HTTP versions [0.9, 1.0, 1.1]. HTTP/2 is currently not supported.
- Only supports status codes that are included in "vlib::http::status".

Examples

#include <vlib/sockets/http.h>
vlib::http::Response response;

Request

vlib::http::Request
HTTP request type.
struct Request;

Notes

- Only supports HTTP versions [0.9, 1.0, 1.1]. HTTP/2 is currently not supported.
- Only supports status codes that are included in "vlib::http::status".
- GET request parameters are by default passed in the payload body. You can use the "Request" functions seperately to create a request that conforms to your wishes.

Examples

#include <vlib/sockets/http.h>
vlib::http::Request request;

Constructor

vlib::http::Request::Request
Construct a request from the server side in string format.
Member 
constexpr 
vlib::http::Request(String data);

Parameters

String
data
Required
The request in string format.

Examples

vlib::String data;
data << "GET /hello_world HTTP/1.1\r\n"
data << "Content-Type:application/json\r\n"
data << "\r\n"

vlib::http::Request request(data);

Constructor

Client

vlib::http::Client
HTTP client type.
template <
    uchar family = sockets::family::ipv4, 
    int type = sockets::type::stream, 
    int protocol = sockets::protocol::undefined, 
    uint buff_len = 1024, 
    bool blocking = false, 
    uint http_version = http::version::v1_1
> 
requires (family == sockets::family::ipv4 ||family == sockets::family::ipv6)

struct Client;

vlib::http::Client(http::ClientTemplateArgs args);

http::ClientTemplateArgs
args
Required
The template arguments.

The arguments can contain the following fields:
struct ClientTemplateArgs {
    String    host;
    String    ip;
    uint    port = 0;
    String              sni;
    String     api_key;
    String     api_secret;
    http::Headers  headers;
    Compression   compression;
};
.

Examples

vlib::http::Client client({
    .host = ...,
    .ip = ...,
    .port = ...,
    .sni = ...,
    .headers = ...,
});

Request

vlib::http::Client::request
Make a HTTP request.
Member 
constexpr 
Response request(
    short method, 
    const String& endpoint, 
    int timeout = 900000 // 15 minutes in milliseconds.#endif
);

Parameters

short
method
Required
The HTTP method, see vlib::http::method for more info.
const String&
endpoint
Required
The endpoint url, for example /.
int
timeout
The timout in milliseconds, use -1 for no timeout.

Return

Response
The functions return a vlib::http::Response object.

Examples

// Request with no parameters.
vlib::http::Client client (...);
vlib::http::Response response = client.request(
    vlib::http::method::get,
    "/",
    -1
)

// Request with a string body.
vlib::http::Response response = client.request(
    vlib::http::method::get,
    "/",
    -1,
    "Hello World!"
)

// Request with json body parameters.
// Use query request to make a request with query parameters.
vlib::http::Response response = client.request(
    vlib::http::method::get,
    "/",
    -1,
    {{"Hello", "World!"}}
)

Client

vlib::https::Client
HTTPS client type.
template <
    uchar family = sockets::family::ipv4, 
    int type = sockets::type::stream, 
    int protocol = sockets::protocol::undefined, 
    uint buff_len = 1024, 
    bool blocking = false, 
    uint tls_version = tls::version::v1_3, 
    uint http_version = http::version::v1_1
> 
requires (family == sockets::family::ipv4 ||family == sockets::family::ipv6)

struct Client;

SMTP Mail

vlib::smtp::Mail
A SMTP Mail object for the SMTP Client.

The mail supports HTML format.

Addresses can contain a single email addres or a name and email address.

The function Mail::build() is automatically called in SMTP::Client::send().
struct Mail;

Examples

#include <vlib/sockets/smtp.h>
vlib::smtp::Mail mail {
    .sender = {"Sender Name", "sender@email.com"},
    .recipients = {
        {"Recipient Name", "recipient1@email.com"},
        {"recipient2@email.com"},
    },
    .cc_recipients = {},
    .bcc_recipients = {},
    .subject = "Example Mail",
    .body = "Hello World!",
    .attachments = {"/path/to/image.png "}
};

SMTP Client

vlib::smtp::Client
A simple SMTP client to send emails.

Make sure SPF and DKIM are properly set up when sending attachments.
This object is still experimental and may contain bugs.
struct Client;

Examples

#include <vlib/sockets/smtp.h>
vlib::smtp::Client client ({
    .host = "smtp.domain.com",
    .port = 465,
    .email = "user@domain.com",
    .pass = "MyPass!",
    .debug = false,
});

Constructor

vlib::smtp::Client::ConstructArgs
Construct the SMTP Client.
Member 
struct ConstructArgs;

Examples

#include <vlib/sockets/smtp.h>
vlib::smtp::Client client ({
    String  host;
    Int     port = 465;
    String  email;
    String  pass;
    String  domain;
    RSA     dkim;
    Int     timeout = 30 * 1000;
    Bool    debug = false;
});
